  "prompt": "Who invented the concept of money?",
  "response": "The concept of money evolved over time and cannot be attributed to a single inventor. It developed independently in different regions of the world as societies grew more complex and the limitations of barter systems became apparent. \n\nThe earliest forms of money were commodities that had intrinsic value, like cattle, grains, or shells. Over time, people began using metal objects as money because they were durable, divisible, and portable. The first known standardized coins were minted in the ancient kingdom of Lydia, in what is now Turkey, around 600 BCE. These Lydian coins contributed significantly to the development of money as we understand it today.\n\nMoney continued to evolve with the introduction of paper currency, which was first developed in China during the Tang Dynasty in the 7th century and became widespread during the Song Dynasty. The modern banking system and electronic money further developed in later centuries, greatly influenced by European and global economic practices.\n\nThus, the \"invention\" of money was a gradual process shaped by various cultures and societies over thousands of years.",
